'''Kawasukuné Shrine''' (かわすくねじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Hakojima, {{ill|lt=Higashiagatsuma Town|Q1203419|qid=Q1203419|1=Higashiagatsuma, Gunma}}, {{ill|lt=Agatsuma District|Q642394|qid=Q642394|1=Agatsuma District, Gunma}}, {{ill|lt=Gunma Prefecture|Q129499|qid=Q129499|1=Gunma Prefecture}}. The enshrined deities are {{ill|lt=Hayaaikitsuhiko and Hayaaikitsuhime|Q11326733|qid=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko-no-Kami|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}} and Hayaakitsuhime-no-Kami{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|lt=Village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.

=== History ===
It is said that {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ono no Kaneyoshi|1=UNKNOWN}}—who was {{ill|lt=exiled|Q1770529|qid=Q1770529|lt=banished|1=Penal transportation}} to {{ill|lt=Kōzuke Province|Q1054838|qid=Q1054838|1=Kōzuke Province}} on suspicion of involvement in the rebellion of {{ill|lt=Prince Sawara|Q1079634|qid=Q1079634|1=Prince Sawara}}—transferred (kanjō) the deity from {{ill|lt=Kawashima Kawasukune Shrine|Q66085130|qid=Q66085130|lt=Kawashima Kawasukune Shrine|1=Kawasukune Shrine (Shibukawa)}} in {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 4 ({{ill|lt=785|Q30554|qid=Q30554|1=785}}){{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.

Interpreting “Kōha” as “river” and “Sukune” as “straight root,” the shrine name is understood to mean “the main current of the river.” Because three shrines with “shima” (island) in their place names—Hakojima, {{ill|lt=Takeuchi Shrine (Shibukawa City)|Q66085129|qid=Q66085129|lt=Sobajima|1=Takeuchi Shrine}}, and Kawashima—were aligned along the {{ill|lt=Agatsuma River|Q1636255|qid=Q1636255|1=Agatsuma River}}, {{ill|lt=Kizao Ozaki|Q21698487|qid=Q21698487|1=Kisao Ozaki}} explains that the river itself was deified<ref>{{Cite book|ja |title=Research on the Jōzuke Province Jinmyōchō |date=1974-12-10 |year=1974 |publisher=Ozaki-sensei Book Publication Society |pages=210–212 |last=Ozaki |first=Kizao |author-link=Kizao Ozaki |doi=10.11501/12266236}}{{Registration required}}</ref>.

During the {{ill|lt=Sengoku period (Japan)|Q204023|qid=Q204023|lt=Sengoku period|1=Sengoku period}}, the shrine was revered by the {{ill|lt=Nagao clan|Q1655561|qid=Q1655561|1=Nagao clan}}, lords of {{ill|lt=Shirai Castle|Q11579353|qid=Q11579353|1=Shirai Castle}}, and it is said that {{ill|lt=Nagao Kageharu|Q247926|qid=Q247926|1=Nagao Kageharu}} dedicated a sword{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}.

In {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 4 ({{ill|lt=1664|Q7581|qid=Q7581|1=1664}}), it possessed shrine lands of 1 tan 3 se 25 bu of rice fields and 1 tan 7 se 4 bu of dry fields as a Daimyōjin shrine{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}. During the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was called “Sukune Daimyōjin,” but in the {{ill|lt=Meiji era|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era}} it was renamed Kawasukune Shrine{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}. Until the Edo period, rituals were conducted by the head priest of Manpuku-ji, the shrine’s {{ill|lt=bettō-ji|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|lt=administrative temple|1=Bettō-ji}}, but since the Meiji period they have been conducted by Shinto priests{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|qid=Q7717|1=1868}}), all old records were lost in a fire at the shrine office{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.

Based on architectural style, the main hall is estimated to date from the early 18th century, and the worship hall from the late 18th century{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.

=== Enshrined Deities ===
The following two water deities are enshrined{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}{{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Regional Revitalization Department, Cultural Properties Protection Division|2022|pp=332–335}}.
* {{ill|lt=Hayaaikitsuhiko and Hayaaikitsuhime|Q11326733|qid=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko-no-Kami|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}
* {{ill|lt=Hayaaikitsuhiko and Hayaaikitsuhime|Q11326733|qid=Q11326733|lt=Hayaakitsuhime-no-Kami|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}

There are 58 subsidiary shrines within the precincts{{Sfn|Azuma Village History Compilation Committee|1965|pp=674–676}}.

